This is a question I genuinely love, because almost everyone gets it wrong in the same way — they recreate MIDI and call it a day. Note, Chord, Measure, Track, Song. Congratulations, you've built a spreadsheet that happens to contain pitches.

The reason that's wrong is that **it's not how musicians think about music.** A musician doesn't think "C4 for 500ms." They think "a step down that lands on the downbeat and resolves the tension." Music is *relational*, not absolute. Let me sketch what taking that seriously looks like.

## The Core Insight

Music has three tensions most representations fumble:

1. **Horizontal vs. Vertical** — melody and harmony aren't separate systems. A chord progression *is* a set of melodies (voice leading). A melody *implies* harmony. Your data structure should make this duality visible, not hide it in separate `Melody` and `Harmony` classes.

2. **Discrete vs. Continuous** — notes are discrete, but dynamics, tempo, and expression are continuous curves *draped over* the discrete structure. Most representations force everything into one or the other.

3. **Multi-scale structure** — a note exists simultaneously at the note level, phrase level, section level, and form level, and its *meaning changes at each scale*. The same V-I is a local resolution AND the end of a 32-bar form.

## The Design

```dart
/// --- PITCH: Relative, not absolute ---

/// The atomic unit isn't a note name. It's an interval.
/// "C" means nothing. "minor 3rd above the local tonic" means everything.
enum IntervalQuality { perfect, major, minor, augmented, diminished }

class Interval {
  final int degree;           // 1-7 (unison through seventh)
  final IntervalQuality quality;
  final int octaveDisplacement; // 0 = simple interval, 1 = compound, etc.

  int get semitones => _computeSemitones();
  Interval operator +(Interval other) => _stack(other);
  Interval get inversion => Interval(9 - degree, _invertQuality(quality));
}

/// A pitch exists only within a tonal context.
/// This is the controversial choice — and it's right.
class ScaleDegree {
  final int degree;              // 1-7
  final Accidental accidental;   // natural, sharp, flat
  final int octave;              // register

  /// The same scale degree means different things in different contexts.
  /// That's not a bug, it's the point.
  Pitch realize(TonalContext context) => context.resolve(this);
}

/// Tonal context is a first-class, mutable, stackable thing.
/// Because modulation is music's most powerful structural tool.
class TonalContext {
  final PitchClass tonic;
  final ScaleType mode;         // major, minor, dorian, whole-tone, etc.
  final List<ScaleDegree> alterations; // borrowed notes, secondary dominants

  TonalContext modulate(Interval by) => /* new context */;
  TonalContext borrow(TonalContext from, {required List<int> degrees}) => /* mix */;

  /// How "far" is another context? (circle of fifths distance, etc.)
  /// This captures why V/V feels close but bVI feels distant.
  double distance(TonalContext other) => _computeDistance(other);
}

/// --- RHYTHM: Hierarchical pulse, not flat durations ---

/// Duration is relative to a pulse, not absolute milliseconds.
/// Because a quarter note at 60bpm and 120bpm are the "same rhythm."
class RhythmicValue {
  final Fraction beatFraction;   // 1/4, 3/8, etc.
  final bool isDotted;
  final TupletContext? tuplet;   // for triplets, quintuplets, etc.
}

/// Meter isn't just a time signature — it's a hierarchy of strong/weak.
class Meter {
  final int beats;
  final int subdivision;
  final List<Accent> accentPattern; // [strong, weak, medium, weak] for 4/4

  /// Where does this rhythmic position sit in the hierarchy?
  /// Beat 1 > Beat 3 > Beats 2,4 > offbeats > sub-offbeats.
  /// This is what "groove" actually is, structurally.
  MetricWeight weightAt(Fraction position);
}

/// --- THE INTERESTING PART: Composable musical gestures ---

/// A "note" is the least interesting unit. A gesture is where music lives.
/// This is the equivalent of going from characters to words to sentences.
sealed class MusicalEvent {
  final RhythmicValue duration;
  final Dynamics dynamics;
  final Articulation? articulation;
}

class Sounding extends MusicalEvent {
  final ScaleDegree pitch;
}

class Rest extends MusicalEvent {}

/// A motif is a *pattern* — an abstract shape that can be transposed,
/// inverted, retrograded, augmented. It's defined by its intervals
/// and rhythmic ratios, NOT by its absolute notes.
class Motif {
  final List<Interval> intervalPattern;
  final List<Fraction> rhythmicRatios;  // relative durations
  final Contour contour;                // up/down/leap/step shape

  /// Apply transformations — this is how development sections work.
  Motif transpose(Interval by);
  Motif invert();                       // flip intervals
  Motif retrograde();                   // reverse
  Motif augment(Fraction factor);       // stretch rhythm
  Motif diminish(Fraction factor);      // compress rhythm

  /// Realize into actual events within a context.
  List<MusicalEvent> realize(ScaleDegree startingPitch, TonalContext context);
}

/// --- HARMONY: Voice leading, not chord symbols ---

/// A "chord" is a snapshot. Voice leading is the actual thing.
/// This is the hill I will die on.
class Voicing {
  final List<ScaleDegree> voices;  // bottom to top

  /// The harmonic tension isn't in the chord — it's in the relationship
  /// between this voicing and its context.
  HarmonicTension tensionIn(TonalContext context);
}

class VoiceLeading {
  final Voicing from;
  final Voicing to;

  /// Each voice moves by some interval (or stays).
  List<Interval?> get motions;

  /// Voice leading quality — parallel fifths, contrary motion, etc.
  /// This is what makes progressions sound good or bad,
  /// and it's invisible in a chord-symbol representation.
  Set<VoiceLeadingProperty> get properties;
}

/// A harmonic progression is a path through tonal space.
class HarmonicProgression {
  final List<(Voicing, RhythmicValue)> chords;
  final TonalContext context;

  List<VoiceLeading> get voiceLeadings;

  /// Does this progression resolve? How strongly?
  /// A plagal cadence resolves differently than an authentic one.
  CadenceType? get cadence;

  /// Harmonic rhythm — how fast are the chords changing
  /// relative to the meter? This is hugely expressive and
  /// almost never modeled.
  List<Fraction> get harmonicRhythm;
}

/// --- CONTINUOUS EXPRESSION: Curves over structure ---

/// Expression isn't a property of a note. It's a curve draped
/// over a span of time. A crescendo doesn't belong to any single note.
sealed class ExpressionCurve {
  final Fraction startPosition;
  final Fraction endPosition;
}

class DynamicCurve extends ExpressionCurve {
  final Dynamics startLevel;
  final Dynamics endLevel;
  final CurveShape shape;  // linear, exponential, subito
}

class TempoCurve extends ExpressionCurve {
  final double startBPM;
  final double endBPM;
  final CurveShape shape;  // rit., accel., a tempo
}

/// --- MULTI-SCALE STRUCTURE: The real payoff ---

/// Musical structure is recursive but NOT a simple tree.
/// Phrases overlap barlines. Elisions exist. Hypermeter ≠ meter.
sealed class MusicalStructure {
  final String? label;
  final List<ExpressionCurve> expression;
}

/// The leaf: a sequence of events in a context.
class Passage extends MusicalStructure {
  final TonalContext context;
  final Meter meter;
  final List<MusicalEvent> events;
  final HarmonicProgression? harmony;
}

/// A phrase — the "sentence" of music.
/// Has an arc: tension builds to a climax and resolves (or doesn't).
class Phrase extends MusicalStructure {
  final List<MusicalStructure> children;
  final Fraction climaxPosition;        // where's the peak?
  final CadenceType ending;             // how does it close?

  /// Phrases can overlap! Elision: the last note of one phrase
  /// is the first note of the next. This is un-representable
  /// in a strict tree, which is why most formats punt on it.
  final ElisionType? elisionWithNext;
}

/// Sections and form — the architecture.
class Section extends MusicalStructure {
  final List<Phrase> phrases;
  final SectionRole role;  // exposition, development, recapitulation,
                           // verse, chorus, bridge, etc.
}

class Form extends MusicalStructure {
  final List<Section> sections;
  final FormType type;     // sonata, rondo, AABA, 12-bar blues, through-composed

  /// Which sections are "the same material"? This captures
  /// the A-B-A relationship that defines most musical forms.
  Map<String, List<Section>> get thematicGroups;
}

/// --- THE WHOLE PIECE ---

class Piece {
  final String? title;
  final Form form;
  final List<Voice> voices;  // instruments/parts
  final Map<Voice, List<MusicalStructure>> parts;

  /// The single most important thing: how do the parts relate?
  /// Counterpoint, homophony, heterophony, call-and-response...
  TextureType textureAt(Fraction position);
}
```

## Why This Is Different

Three choices that matter:

**Pitch is relative.** There's no `Note('C4')` anywhere. Everything is a scale degree in a context. To get an absolute pitch you *must* provide a tonal context. This means transposition is free (just change the context), and analysis is built into the representation rather than bolted on.

**Harmony is voice leading.** A `Voicing` is a snapshot, but the real object is `VoiceLeading` — the *motion between* snapshots. This makes it natural to talk about parallel fifths, contrary motion, and resolution. Chord symbols are a lossy compression of this; I'm storing the actual thing.

**Expression is continuous and structural, not per-note.** A crescendo is a curve over a time span, living at the phrase or section level. It's not `note.velocity = 87`. This mirrors how performers actually think — "this phrase builds toward beat 3 of measure 4" — rather than assigning loudness to individual atoms.

The thing I'm most excited about is `Motif` with its transformations. A fugue subject that gets inverted, augmented, and stacked on top of itself in stretto — that's all just method calls on the same object. The *identity* of the motif survives the transformation, which is exactly how we hear it. Most representations destroy that identity the moment you transpose.

What I *didn't* model (and someone would need to eventually): timbre, microtonal pitch, aleatoric/indeterminate sections, and the gnarly edge cases of spectral music where the harmony/timbre distinction collapses. Those are all fascinating problems but they'd triple the surface area.

Okay, here's the thing — email validation is one of those problems where everyone thinks they know the answer, and almost everyone is wrong.

The "correct" regex for RFC 5322 email addresses is famously a multi-page monstrosity. Most people slap on a basic regex and call it a day, which rejects valid addresses like `"weird but legal"@example.com` or `user+tag@[IPv6:::1]`. Meanwhile, the only *real* validation is "send them an email and see if they click the link."

So let me write something that's honest about what it's actually doing — a practical filter, not a standards-compliant parser — and that's clear about the tradeoffs:

```dart
/// A pragmatic email validator that's honest about its limitations.
///
/// This does NOT validate against RFC 5322 (which permits things like
/// quoted strings, comments, and IP literals that no real service accepts).
/// Instead, it validates against what real-world email providers actually
/// support — which is a much narrower and more useful definition.
///
/// Returns a [ValidationResult] explaining exactly why something failed,
/// because "invalid email" is the worst error message in computing.
ValidationResult validateEmail(String input) {
  if (input.isEmpty) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid('You gave me nothing to work with.');
  }

  final trimmed = input.trim();
  if (trimmed != input) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'Leading/trailing whitespace — probably a copy-paste artifact.',
    );
  }

  final parts = input.split('@');
  if (parts.length != 2) {
    return parts.length < 2
        ? ValidationResult.invalid('No @ sign. That\'s not an email, that\'s a username.')
        : ValidationResult.invalid(
            'Multiple @ signs. If you meant a literal @, the RFC says to '
            'quote it, but no real mail provider will accept that anyway.',
          );
  }

  final [local, domain] = parts;

  if (local.isEmpty) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid('Nothing before the @. Who are you?');
  }
  if (local.length > 64) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'Local part is ${local.length} chars. RFC 5321 caps it at 64.',
    );
  }
  if (local.startsWith('.') || local.endsWith('.')) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'Local part starts or ends with a dot — technically RFC-illegal '
      'and Gmail will bounce it.',
    );
  }
  if (local.contains('..')) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'Consecutive dots in local part. RFC says no, providers agree.',
    );
  }

  // What real providers actually allow (not the full RFC insanity)
  final localRegex = RegExp(r"^[a-zA-Z0-9.!#$%&'*+/=?^_`{|}~-]+$");
  if (!localRegex.hasMatch(local)) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'Local part has characters that are technically RFC-valid in quoted '
      'strings but that zero real mail servers accept. Be normal.',
    );
  }

  if (domain.isEmpty) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid('Nothing after the @. Where should this go?');
  }
  if (domain.length > 253) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'Domain is ${domain.length} chars. DNS caps hostnames at 253.',
    );
  }

  // Reject IP literals — yes they're valid, no they're not real emails
  if (domain.startsWith('[')) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'IP literal domain. Technically valid per RFC 5321, but if someone '
      'gives you user@[192.168.1.1] as their email, they\'re messing with you.',
    );
  }

  final domainParts = domain.split('.');
  if (domainParts.length < 2) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'Domain has no dot. user@localhost is valid for your dev box, '
      'not for production.',
    );
  }

  final tld = domainParts.last;
  if (tld.length < 2) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'TLD "$tld" is too short. Single-char TLDs don\'t exist (yet).',
    );
  }
  if (RegExp(r'^\d+$').hasMatch(tld)) {
    return ValidationResult.invalid(
      'All-numeric TLD. That\'s not a thing. '
      'You might be looking at an IP address.',
    );
  }

  final domainRegex = RegExp(r'^[a-zA-Z0-9]([a-zA-Z0-9-]*[a-zA-Z0-9])?$');
  for (final label in domainParts) {
    if (label.isEmpty) {
      return ValidationResult.invalid('Empty label in domain (consecutive dots).');
    }
    if (label.length > 63) {
      return ValidationResult.invalid(
        'Domain label "$label" exceeds 63 chars. DNS won\'t resolve it.',
      );
    }
    if (!domainRegex.hasMatch(label)) {
      return ValidationResult.invalid(
        'Domain label "$label" has invalid characters. '
        'Hyphens are fine, but not at the start or end.',
      );
    }
  }

  return ValidationResult.ok();
}

class ValidationResult {
  final bool isValid;
  final String? reason;

  const ValidationResult._(this.isValid, this.reason);
  const ValidationResult.ok() : this._(true, null);
  const ValidationResult.invalid(String reason) : this._(false, reason);

  @override
  String toString() => isValid ? 'Valid' : 'Invalid: $reason';
}
```

The thing I actually care about here: **every rejection tells you exactly why**. The number of login forms that just say "invalid email" when you typo'd one character is criminal. The error messages are also slightly opinionated because validation *is* opinionated — you're drawing a line between "I'll accept this" and "I won't," and you should own that.

The other honest thing: this explicitly rejects stuff that's technically RFC-valid but that no human has ever used as a real email address. Quoted local parts, IP literal domains, comments inside addresses — the RFC permits a lot of wild stuff that exists only in spec documents and CTF challenges. A validator that accepts `"(comment)john"@[IPv6:::1]` isn't more correct, it's just more confused about its purpose.
